Abstract = {Conservation finance is a nascent field that claims to deliver maximum
   conservation impacts, while, at the same time, generating returns for
   investors (Credit Suisse/WWF). While geographers have questioned the
   ability of conservation finance to play a significant role in
   international biodiversity conservation, an emerging cohort of boutique
   private equity firms are actively generating returns on North American
   conservation projects. This raises the question: how are these firms
   generating profits, and in turn, returns for their shareholders? Drawing
   from a Marxian understanding of finance as redistributive, I argue that
   these firms are generating profits through a process similar to a
   corporate hostile takeover. Using the examples of ranchland and
   timberland investment in the United States, I show that (1) the
   materialities and historical geographies of these landscapes play a
   crucial role their monetization, and (2) shareholder returns are
   generated through a combination of traditional real estate sales and
